	url = {https://oxford.universitypressscholarship.com/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780198744047.001.0001/acprof-9780198744047-chapter-11},
	abstract = {It is reasonable to expect that many existing environmental drivers of migration will be sensitive to climate change, especially in the developing world. A particularly conspicuous cause of environmental displacement is rising sea levels. Regional variances in sea-level rise will likely result in Small Island States (SISs) suffering disproportionate consequences in terms of land loss, even total submersion. This chapter argues that the citizens of SISs who become territorially dispossessed are in danger of becoming stateless persons unless institutional innovations are made. This chapter argues that the territorially dispossessed should be provided with a ‘Passport for the Territorially Dispossessed’ (PTD). All states have an obligation to accept holders of this new passport and to permit them to be naturalized. This means that the territorially dispossessed have a right to choose their new nationality.},
